Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law introducing administrative liability for violating the terms and order of payment for goods (works, services) when purchasing for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve the very acute problem of non-fulfillment of obligations by customers when carrying out public and municipal purchases.
Two years ago, the situation of entrepreneurs not being able to get paid for government and municipal contracts that had already been executed was widespread.
Then the President of Russia gave the General Prosecutor's Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who made contracts without financial backing, tried to evade their payment obligations, and included illegal terms in contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the prosecutor's office has submitted 9,7 thousand submissions, according to the results of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to administrative, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigating bodies for organizing procedural checks, 46 of them criminal cases have been initiated.
The result was a debt of more than 66 billion rubles to the entrepreneurs.
And the vast sums of money accumulated were far from the result of a multibillion-dollar default.
The debt has been so great that many entrepreneurs have been systematically delayed in paying their services for much more modest amounts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition to provide social transportation services for several million rubles.
The man put all his money into the bank, fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial pile of debt, including salaries, taxes, and loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor's office.
The problem has been brought to a minimum in a number of regions.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt levels continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor's office works in a manual anti-crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally holds outbound meetings with local authorities, where all violations discovered by the prosecutors are examined in detail and measures taken to immediately eliminate them.
Such operational meetings have already taken place in Yaroslavl and Ekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in the Part of Establishing Administrative Responsibility of the Official Persons of the Customer for Violation of the Term and Order of Payment of Goods (Works, Services) When Purchasing for State and Municipal Needs" will be able to improve the payment discipline of public buyers.
The bill was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by a customer's official of the term and order of payment for goods, works and services during state and municipal purchases.
If the official has already been sentenced for a similar offense, he will be disqualified for one to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already received instructions to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
A civil rights group has issued a travel warning in Missouri .
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's Travel Warning, effective August 28, 2017, urges African American travelers, guests and citizens of Missouri to exercise extra caution and caution when traveling in the state in light of a number of suspected racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are listed here".
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the movement warning was prompted by a recent law in Missouri that made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement officers' disproportionate targeting of minorities.
You have people who are subjected to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed", Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star.
We hear complaints more often than ever before.
This is the first such warning issued by the organization against a U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racially humiliated treatment of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while on a state trip, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office that found that black drivers were 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is to make people aware and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
People should be prepared in one way or another whether they take bail money with them or inform relatives that they are traveling across state lines.
According to the FBI's latest hate crime reporting program, Missouri had 100 hate crimes in 2015, making it the 16th largest state in the nation.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that will make it harder to sue a legal entity for housing or employment discrimination.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings in Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said should increase racial screening.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, NGOs have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
