You know, I've had a reflex since I was a kid, you can't throw a candy bar across the road, you get a ticket.
And now there are video cameras everywhere.
And indeed, the sidewalks in downtown Singapore are as clean as a museum.
Chang says that three months ago, his neighbor's 18-year-old son graffitied the wall of an old colonial building.
The court found the guy guilty of vandalism and sentenced him to probation.
What?!
I mean, imagine that.
He received ten wooden batons on his buttocks and spent a week in prison.
We have a lot of corporal punishment.
The high standard of living and the harsh laws in Singapore were explored by the AIF.
No one is thinking of abolishing the death penalty here, explains lawyer Victor Lee Hong.
And the government has long been indifferent to what the European Union and the United States think about this.
If a person carries a large quantity of drugs or sells them, he is hanged.
In 2002, a 22-year-old Australian man was arrested at Changi Airport carrying 400 grams of cocaine.
The Australian prime minister, international human rights groups, and even the pope have come out in his defense, threatening sanctions.
But the guy was hanged anyway.
After that, the drug runners are painstakingly circling our country.
The thing is, in Singapore, the law is supposed to be obeyed by EVERYONE, not just the poor and the rich.
It doesn't matter who you are, a millionaire, a deputy prime minister, a famous artist or a European Union citizen.
The only option in this case is if they find half a kilo of cocaine in your possession, you're hanged.
When you walk around Singapore and you see signs with warning signs everywhere, you're just amazed at how much is prohibited in this city-state.
For example, chewing gum is only available in pharmacies and can be purchased strictly on a prescription.
Tourists don't get chewed on arrival, but if they stick gum on the subway, they get a fine of 1,000 local dollars.
In four days, I met two people with white signs around their necks saying, "I'm a garbage man".
In addition to fines, a cigarette can often be sentenced to "conviction in a prison": a week of cleaning parks and beaches.
6 thousand rubles. The "criminal" who forgets to wash the water in the public toilet, and when trying to do a small needle in the elevator of the house, a special detector works - the doors are blocked and a signal is sent to the police.
Some of the most exotic laws include bans on feeding pigeons on the street, public singing, and even excessive watering of indoor plants (!).
To avoid fires, smokers are not allowed to carry lighters on the subway, or they will be fined 5,000 Singapore dollars.
So, you get the idea that no matter how hard you try, you're bound to break something.
That's not true, says Mohammed Kabir-Kajaria, owner of a local travel agency.
The most fantastic laws exist only on paper, and in the last 20 years I have not seen anyone convicted of breaking them.
Why are they preserved?
So the citizens don't get too comfortable.
The basic rules are strictly observed.
For example, if a cigarette is sold to a minor at a cigarette stand, the store owner will pay a large fine, the offender will be beaten in the back, and the seller will also be flogged and imprisoned.
It is because of such strict laws that crime is very rare in Singapore.
Is that justified?
Back in the 1970's, we had a lot of chaos on the road, with drivers ignoring traffic lights, driving as they pleased, getting drunk and driving.
After the fines, it's been a year since the whole thing went down.
Now the driver, having drunk a shot of whiskey, knows that if he is stopped, the cop will not let him go for the bribe, will fine him the price of the apartment and send him to jail for years.
To many foreigners, the city-state in Southeast Asia seems like a kind of concentration camp.
In 1993, American writer William Gibson called Singapore "Disneyland with the death penalty" - a US visitor was horrified by the overall wealth of its residents, "the eerily clean airport" and "the cultured nature".
They say things like this are unnatural, they look artificial, and they shouldn't be.
First day in Singapore, you're afraid to throw a piece of paper on the sidewalk, you're afraid to get on the subway with ice cream.
But then you come to Little India, and suddenly there's a pattern breaking: plastic cups lying around the bus stop.
"What's that?" you wonder.
And that's how Singaporeans smile.
It's not the end of the world.
Not every "crime" like this gets caught on the spot, but you should know: If you get caught, you're not getting away with it - you broke the law.
Most of the time, that's enough to make a person behave normally.
Of course, the government in Singapore is quite authoritarian.
But you know what?
I was very careful when I was in Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, because motorcyclists often snatch smartphones and cameras from tourists.
Downtown Paris is full of dirty tramps and beggars.
Not everyone on our streets is trying to throw trash in the dumpster.
Singapore, with its draconian fines and ruthless laws (including the death penalty), is the most peaceful, clean and safe city on Earth.
You'll think about it.
It's human nature, remember, and in Russia, nobody used to fasten their seat belts while driving until they got a ticket.
Although, in Singapore, it's not the fines that matter, it's voluntary compliance.
And you have to think, in Russia, people would also be happy with clean streets, no trash in the subway and would welcome the arrest of those who confuse the elevator with a public toilet.
I'm not gonna give you any physical punishment.
Otherwise, Singapore's laws are at least worth a look.
Nothing sacred about it?
Now the Trump White House is targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when he starts fighting the statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone else, hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of Saddam Hussein's statue in Baghdad's Firdous Square in 2003.
Steven Miller, one of the key ideologues in the Trump administration, no doubt knew what he was doing when he brought a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a heated argument with CNN reporter Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to drastically reduce legal immigration.
Let's face it, Miller didn't touch the statue itself.
A bunch of cruise ship owners and Statue of Liberty artists would lynch him if he tried to do it.
But he was attacking its meaning, and especially the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed, when the pedestal was added with poems by Emma Lazarus.
As Miller groaned at Acosta, "I don't want to go into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you're talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller's got the facts right, but as he says, it's not really about the story.
It's about the current sound of Lazarus's striking words, the only ones in which the state invites not just any immigrant, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming of breathing free, / the miserable refuse of your abundant shores".
Never before have "unfortunate scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller wasn't a literary scholar -- he made it clear that Trump is not wanted in America.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a larger political and cultural war: it's really a debate about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to have her words placed on the base of the statue after her death - knew full well that they were committing a purely political act.
The sculpture was intended to symbolize the connection between the French and American republics through a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a whole new name:
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
The boisterous Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist who heralded Trump's coming, argued in 2010 that Liberty is not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative, bringing America's flame to a world in darkness: "Freedom is moving forward.
She carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way in the United States".
Against all the odds, Limbo really got the point.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as the tired, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships would see her after a long and often difficult voyage.
It literally means looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking refuge and a chance at a better life.
Her statue answers them with words of hope and hospitality they long to hear.
And that's certainly not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to kindle the hatred that is their only source of strength.
