Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office unless you're ready to hear criticism from voters
The founders of our country knew what critical press was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from his domestic policies to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he didn't shut up his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "You can take away freedom of speech and we, the deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter".
Now I'm going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted posts from at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's staff called the lawsuit moot, and the online commentary was "so what".
"It's just Facebook", many people would say.
But that's important, too.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state.
He's second in the nation's top 50 governors.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in running the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as his primary means of communicating with his constituents and jokingly shows off his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
So blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is run by administration staff on taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, saying that blocking comments is simply moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and hackers that are rampant on the Internet.
The Post talked to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls -- teachers, businessmen, pastors, who are addressing their elected leaders.
All of them say their comments were respectful, meaningful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible to show that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hate but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment saying I was disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news", she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
"I also don't like the idea that when many people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's so-called "screwing" instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens".
What the governor's staff calls a "concentrated spam attack", others would probably call an "active life stance".
In the age of Facebook, it's easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
It's a much less dusty job than before, when it required sending people in, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and silencing protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening now, just in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, groundbreaking decisions on this issue was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Cashearis of Alexandria, the chairwoman of the Laudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington, the era of affordable postal services was about as revolutionary as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous letters greatly eroded his reputation.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People using the aliases "Eurycola", "Valerus", "Belizarus", and "Porcius" wrote letters to the newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and expression is at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means accepting that.
