Poverty and death in the Indonesian Golden Land
When preparing lunch, Bardina Degei does not use a stove.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarothali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just places a sweet potato, called nota, right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred clover is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
DeGei sits on the ground floor  she has no furniture  and it is here that she does her chores, such as washing clothes in muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one dares to walk in the countryside after five o'clock", she says.
It's a rare opportunity to see everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by publicly raising their hands to the occupying forces.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, barring foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enaratali  is as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jaipur, the administrative center of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour drive by hired car.
There's no public transportation here.
The city of about 19,000 people is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of the steel are painted with rust in various reddish shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, have made it, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamei.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also the golden land of Indonesia.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran Company, is just sixty miles from Panicay, a high-mountain province about the size of New Jersey with 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced gold and copper worth about $3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves worth an estimated $78 billion.
This wealth, however, brings a single misfortune to the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains its stifling presence here.
