But in Papua, little has changed, and the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovic, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice", Yow said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Djokovic Paniai was tragically killed.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols at a bonfire in Enarothali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle burst out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javed Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers a short time later.
According to victims and witnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers fired on a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Aimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the Election Commission, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuans men, women and children gathered on a football field outside a local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought their ritual hunting bows and performed waita, a dance of the Papuans called meye pagos, running in circles and imitating the song of birds.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, soldiers were given an order by internal radio: "If the crowd resisted more than three times, shoot them", according to an official document seen by TIME magazine but not published by local media.
Jeremiah Kayame, 56, the district head of Kego Koto in Enaratali, sensed the danger and appealed to the crowd to disperse to their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, I got a bullet in my left wrist", he told TIME magazine from the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the side of a line of soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of gunshots", he adds.
Alfius Youv, a local resident, was shot three times, his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, said.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", said Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
I saw he was dead... I kissed him.
General Yotje Mende, the senior police inspector in Papua, told reporters that his officers were simply "defending" their base because it was under attack.
