For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want an investigation, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice", he says.
"We cannot move to healing and reconciliation until we have justice".
A coroner covers the body of one of the lynch victims at Morse Ford, July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of being involved in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been keenly aware of the two linked motives of the lynchers: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruled that black citizens could vote in the primary that summer.
Around the same time as the election, the FBI reports that black gunman Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently over a woman.
Brooks says that rumors were circulating in town that Hester had slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the child she was to have was not her husband's.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, posted a $600 bond to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins, May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of the prison and into the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of lynchers surrounded the car.
"Harrison is found to have organized and ordered the killings", concludes one FBI report.
"It's also clear that there was a collusion between state and city law enforcement, "which not only participated in the killings, "but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
Brooks calls it short.
"It was an attack on the right to vote", he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to the black people in the city that if you register and vote, you will be the same".
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Green has been directing an annual production of the lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her play is vivid, it captivates the audience and it tells the story of the deep racism that many would like to believe is no longer in America.
It's hard to look at, and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's what's important.
"We don't want to talk about the lynch trials because they show us our own ugliness", she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you don't listen to me or hear what I've been through".
This year's rehearsal began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - gathered in the room and listened to a polished review of the play.
Wade Marbow was the director with Green.
He's been the clan's chief for years, but he says it's never been easier.
"I feel like I'm dirty because that's not who I am", says Marbo.
"But I think it's very important to remember this story, because we don't want to go back to that time".
In the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Raskona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, reprise their roles.
The play begins with Malcolm, enraged that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Rascón shouts back.
It's a hit.
And at that moment, everyone (at least all the black actors) burst out laughing.
Green laughs louder than anyone.
"What is it?" Asks Ascon.
He's worried and confused.
Am I overplaying my hand?
"No", Green says through laughter.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'nigga' back then".
"Yeah, yeah", laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to say the solid 'R'".
And so the energy in the room changes, and the discomfort is replaced by a sense of camaraderie.
Everyone has to do the right thing, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Raskona says the "n" word, it's clear and sharp.
No human being laughs.
The play ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in a black mourning dress stands over the bodies of the actors and sings the sad song "Strange Fruit" by Billie Holiday.
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, half a hundred spectators are wiping their tears and sweat from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of black and white people in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live right next door.
They all endured the heavy spirit of Georgia for nearly eight hours as Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until that point, the murders were just history, but now that they're standing in the same place where people were lynched, it seems like their ghosts are hanging in the air.
As the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children lean over their heads, touch the paint that represents blood and the still bodies, and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead", one little boy mutters, as if to remind himself.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and then it's over.
The actors drop the ropes from their necks and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the head puppet master.
Nick Raskona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the performance finally falls on him.
"It's all right", one of the women whispers.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had your reasons".
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At a table, a white couple from Atlanta are having a lively discussion about a play with a black couple they just met.
Denise Daplinski has difficulty finding words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to hear these horrible, horrible words and actions... from people who look like you and who do it because they look like you", she says.
"After that, I think lynchings still happen", she adds, "only now it's called police shooting".
In the other corner of the room, the attention is drawn to Tyrone Brooks, who is recalling his work as a human rights activist over dinner.
He says he's already started planning a show next year.
"The play is inspiring because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced but also teaches us", he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it".
