The Migrationsverket has so far sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the test subjects were assessed as 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases the forensic medicine agency assessed that the test subject was "likely to be 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, the verdict was that the person was probably under 18.
Tests are only done when age is in doubt.
According to Johan Göransson of the forensic medicine agency, the results are consistent with those of the past few months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics from the past months, the numbers are quite consistent", he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where people were assessed as 18 years old does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency released results from 581 tests and reported that 442 cases were "likely 18 years of age or older".
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases a person openly stated that 18 of them were coming this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves taking a wisdom tooth X-ray and a knee-joint CT scan and giving them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also been criticized in some jurisdictions.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Carolina Institute, whose work includes assessing people's biological maturity to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think we should use the measurement methods that we use now.
Biological age is not determined precisely.
If we can't define it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told Metro.
