How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs will not prevent the world record-setting transfer of Neymar from Barcelona in Spain to Paris Saint-Germain in France.
Whatever consequences may come further down the chain, for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA, the governing body that controls European football, whose power is to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League tournament.
The financial fair play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 suggest that PSG will eventually have to show that Neymar's transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to release the Brazilian from his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG could certainly make a fortune to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from Qatar's energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums on players, but they have to balance it against legitimate revenue to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that go into huge debt in their quest for success are in fact cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners stop funding.
In 2011, the FFP stopped focusing on club debts and instead switched to tracking their losses.
This change in business model, which was originally used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003  to buy a club with good potential, and then spend heavily in order to improve the team and create a world brand  became a difficult plan to implement.
During this three-year assessment period, which is 2018 in the making, the clubs could suffer losses of 30 million euros.
And even though Platini was disgracedly removed from his post as president in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Alexander Cheferin, is still determined to curb excessive spending.
"Of course, the FFP is alive, and we will tighten the rules going forward", Andrea Traverso, UEFA's FFP controller, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay for Neymar's contract at once, it can distribute this sum over the entire term of his contract for reporting purposes.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer fee can be shown in the annual report as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of sanctions against the FA in 2014, the FA imposed severe sanctions on the club, as well as the Abu Dhabi-based Manchester City.
PSG was fined €60 million (at that rate it is $82 million), which was later reduced to €20 million, and was ordered to limit its squad in the Champions League during the 2014-1015 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is tracking clubs that may try to outsmart its financial inspections by inflating their revenue at the expense of companies linked to the club's owners.
While a Qatari company could sponsor PSG, if the funding amount was deemed to be above standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014 when UEFA ruled that the amount of funding for the PSG from Qatar's Tourism Authority was inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar's earnings at PSG may have come in the form of payments from the organising committee for the 2022 world cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will be the ambassador of the World Cup, and such a move could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more vigilant in monitoring any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As people familiar with the situation reported on Thursday, UEFA had not held any preliminary discussions with PSG over Neymar's transfer.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they are not authorized to discuss the PJS situation.
According to the latest published report, in 2015-16, PSJ received more than 10 million euros in profit with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The last financial year's report has not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to be a good platform for sponsorship deals, sales of team attributes and T-shirts.
The club expects a turnover of at least 30 percent due to the new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best footballers is leaving, the Spanish league tried to prevent Neymar's transfer, saying that PSG would violate financial fair play.
"This is a clear case of 'financial doping' by the club and the state", La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, noting that the ultimate owner of PSG is Qatar.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports mogul, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's state funding.
"This is all the result of participation, and it has completely changed the landscape of football over the last 15 years", Wenger said on Thursday.
When the country owns the club, anything is possible.
It's becoming very difficult to keep financial fair play, because a country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The president will determine the order and place of the swearing in .
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies were planning to directly define the oath-taking procedure in the law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as the incapacitated, will be exempt from taking the oath, according to the revised text of amendments to the bill "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available in the "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider before the second reading on July 11 at its meeting.
The idea of introducing an oath when entering into Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with the State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formulated this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading to the bill, which provides for the cancellation of the decision on the issuance of citizenship to those who were later convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the internet (part 2 of article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only in the case if this act is related to terrorism (part 4 of article 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, the logic was that when a person signs a citizenship document, he is promising to abide by Russian law - by taking the path of extremism, he is breaking that promise.
The bill was introduced in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev ("United Russia"), Genny Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Justice Russia") and the speaker of the GD Вячеслав Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Department's Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for second reading, but it has now been revised again.
Now it says the oath-taking procedure will be set by the president of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of the representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, the text of the bill did not make it clear where such an event should take place - the list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, the offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
It could be the registration.
Those who want to become Russian citizens will take the oath after the officials check their documents.
But a Russian passport can only be obtained after taking an oath, according to the revised text.
A week ago, the bill said that the oath should precede the signing of the executive order.
The updated text says that Russia will take the oath at 18, not 14.
The rule that incapacitated or limited-functional persons, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the oath text by hand, are exempt from taking the oath was retained.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure "other persons",
The updated bill also stipulates a special procedure for accepting Ukrainian citizens who are considered Russian speakers.
They will have to officially renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an application to the authorized Ukrainian authority.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The "foreign" citizenship will not be required to be renounced, as it is now, if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible "for reasons beyond the person".
The relevant amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom the first vice-speaker of the GD Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalya Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for a decision on their fate regarding Russian citizenship, - explained the head of the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarifies that the restrictions on certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have written a written refusal to take another citizenship and have handed over their previous passport to the Russian Interior Ministry, but "for reasons beyond their control" have not ceased to be considered citizens of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited from holding positions in municipal services, being accepted for work in facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or residence permit of another country cannot become a member of the State Duma or the Federation Council.
The law is expected to come into force on September 1, 2017, and the necessary legal acts should be ready by then.
