The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce interest rates unchanged later after weak economic growth and weakening inflation dampened rumours of a possible rise.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain sluggish and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on household incomes.
The bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer members of the committee this month voting to raise rates because weak economic growth weakened support for the hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts to 1.7 percent in 2017 and 1.6 percent in 2018, and warned that pressure on household incomes would continue, while it still expects inflation to rise to about 3 percent in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes over the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said borrowing costs would likely have to rise more strongly than expected in financial markets.
The committee also voted to drop part of a massive package of economic development measures launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close its urgent financing plan, which provides banks with cheap loans, although it has said it will now provide another £15 billion to £115 billion under this plan.
In a minutes decision on the rates, the bank said: According to the MPC's main forecasts, gross domestic product (GDP) growth will remain slow in the near term, while pressures on real household incomes continue to affect consumption.
On the issue of interest rates, he reiterated that to halt inflation, "some tightening of fiscal policy" would be required, "somewhat more" than the markets expect.
At this point, markets are predicting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases would be "gradual" and "limited".
The bank's forecast for this and next year's increases is lower than the forecasts made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank kept its forecast unchanged at 1.8% in 2018.
After this news, sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to 1.31 US dollars and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change the rate was made after recent disappointing growth rates weakened the rising expectation of an increase; GDP then rose 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the bank's representative, growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will start to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The bank's latest inflation report gave little reason for happiness to households hit by high inflation and very slight wage increases: the bank said the pressure would increase before declining.
The bank added that fiscal policy "cannot prevent" a drop in earnings in the next few years, but expects wages to "significantly recover" by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of rising demand for British goods, driven by a low pound exchange rate that offsets some of the lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were cut to 0.25% last August after the shock Brexit referendum resulted in a fall in the pound.
The bank estimates that it will likely take four years to fully affect prices and the economy.
Before the bank made its final rate decision, the rumor about the proposed rate hike was growing as inflation pressured the already strained households: three experts on the committee asked for a rate hike to 0.5 percent in July.
