State health service to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to a "revolutionary" HIV drug after a high court battle over funding from the National Health Service.
England's National Health Service announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the NHS during an initial three-year trial period of about 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP, despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was described as a "major innovation" by Simon Stevens, president of England's National Health Service, and a "tipping point" by the National AIDS Control Authority (NAT).
Before the programme is fully rolled out across England by April 2018, venereal clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, with more clinics to join the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP)  is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV among people at high risk.
Taking PrEP before sex is a way to prevent HIV infection by taking a sufficient amount of certain medications.
These drugs can be taken daily or at least two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include gay and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV-positive and are not receiving successful treatment.
Clinical providers will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and people whose partners are not known to have their HIV status contained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation at the nearest venereal clinic participating in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and the NHS in England signed a contract to supply the drug this week after an international tender.
The study was designed to evaluate the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who the drug's target audience is, its uptake and use on a large scale.
This important innovation should complement and reinforce the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in combating one of the greatest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT, said: "This is a watershed moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at people who are in need and at risk, can make a difference to the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, through this study funded by the National Health Service in England, will have access to a new, novel drug that you can control without talking to your partner, and that will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "The first thing we need to do now is to make sure that the trial is rolled out quickly across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that we have the experimental PrEP, we're on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people who are at risk for HIV.
Shadow public health secretary Sharon Hodgson said: "We very much welcome the start of the PrEP trial, which has been very delayed by months of delays and delays from the government".
The data shows how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this deadly infection.
This trial will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It's important now that the trial is rolled out nationwide as soon as possible to protect people at risk of HIV and take us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in our communities.
