Judges are being offered protection from the chairmen
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (PCHR) has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of government on the instructions of Vladimir Putin.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the judges and introduce their electionality.
The Human Rights Council wants to introduce special districts for appellate and cassation courts that are not tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also make its own recommendations under the presidential mandate.
The Human Rights Council has completed the development of proposals to strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
The JCC carried out this work on the instructions of Vladimir Putin dated January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with the members of the council.
At the meeting with the members of the Council on December 8, 2016, individual cases of arbitrariness of the courts were discussed, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Ъ" from December 9).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and detecting judicial errors, and the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If a candidate for the position of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the president of the court, according to the HRC, should present him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases to be considered among the judges.
Experts suggest that a computer program may be used to do this.
The SPHR also considers that the chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification certification of a judge, initiate his disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments".
The presidential council considers it necessary to "elect the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short term with mandatory rotation".
Now all court presidents (from the republican to the district) are appointed for six years by the president on the recommendation of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the Human Rights Council proposes a new way of organizing appeals and cassation in general courts.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Human Rights Council says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts".
The experts are based on the practice of arbitration courts.
They have "judicial districts", which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use the "telephone right".
The Human Rights Council proposes to strengthen the peace judges by popular panels to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, about the loss of parental rights, about the restoration of employment, about the protection of honor and dignity, about the loss of driving license, etc.
"These are only our proposals", explained "Ъ" the member of the SPHR, retired judge of the Constitutional Court Tamara Morshakova.
She also reminded that the president's instructions were not only for the SPHR, but also for the Supreme Court (SV), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time to fulfill the task at the Supreme Court (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Russian human rights commissioner).
The Supreme Court chairman, Vyacheslav Lebedev, must report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of the judiciary is being ensured in Russia by September 1.
Living high: Half-floor and sleek design techniques turned this little apartment in Earls Court into a spacious home
Joan Lee, a former banker who is passionate about real estate, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a nice Queen Anne-style house, and the new design is a testament to the fact that Joan didn't pack up her things and move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge, a much larger area", says Joan.
I was looking for something to match my money.
They showed me this apartment in Earl's Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.
Since the first time I saw it, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has been completely remodeled.
Originally, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout  to get to the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen  and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a second floor to maximize the benefits of the generous ceiling height.
I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
"These were my demands", she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck & Shed to use the 12.5 foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project but would be suitable for Joan to live in.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms on top of each other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to be creative to handle the briefing.
"It's very difficult to work with steel", he explains.
We had to arrange the rooms so that they were on top of each other and not have to bend.
It was not just a simple platform, but a curve to make it at the right height to allow for the use of the space above and below.
This solution allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one on top of the other in the space allocated  and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from Retrouvius, you can see the lavish living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold trim, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muy define the style of the project.
Mirrors play a role in adding spectacle, space, and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror panel looks like a window to another room.
The mirror cabinets at the entrance are for keeping all of Joan's dishes.
To create a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when not in use.
There's nothing new about folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a sliding door that goes up like a garage door.
"This was an engineering feat", Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber shield door.
It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.
By using space and storage wisely, Joan gained an additional 50 square feet [16 sq m], an additional bedroom, and improved layout.
"At the end of the day, floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, which is how your property is valued", Erfan says.
Basically, a real estate agent will come in and calculate the floor area.
Here, they were able to increase the floor area using high-quality materials that give the space a luxurious feel.
 Materials  are what we touch, so they help to create an emotional connection to the home, says Erfan.
Nobody falls in love with wiring in a wall.
It's important, but it doesn't touch the strings of our hearts.
This is proof that with good design and increased footprint, a condo can go from something ordinary to something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
The government approved the creation of a commission on cultural policy
The Russian government approved the creation of a commission on state cultural policy.
The relevant decree is published on the government website.
