Brothers fighting for a $ 500 million real estate empire
Two brothers fight for one of Victoria's largest real estate empires worth over $500 million - forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin de Lutyens lives in the Turak Palace three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a property and assets division lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court.
Paul has been trying to get out of the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in the middle of a heated dispute over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother, Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, purchased since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew to a network of 160 stores.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's list of holdings today includes office buildings, development lots in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mount Buller, and shopping centers in the suburbs.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as "the main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, that means Colin's assets are $316 million and Paul's are $176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
"The division Colin proposed gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property", he wrote in his first deposition in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed reconciliation attempts, the first hearings were held in the Supreme Court.
The brothers are now fighting over who will control the existing business - from which Paul believes Colin has removed him.
Colin claims that's not true, but he accuses Paul of mismanaging some of the facilities.
In Colin's testimony at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes the dispute will be resolved.
"My Italian roots make me consider family a top priority", he wrote.
The legal costs are snowballing, with hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer, and both sides have drawn the best lawyers, including Crown Counsel Alan Myers, and the best cookers.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran dairy bars and gastronomes, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
With financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the family's first jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last year of high school, and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old)".
Anna De Lutis says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass on their property to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi often told me that he did not want the brothers to go to court", she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colina says Mark received $10 million when he went out of business and Luke $26 million.
Paul says that both Luke and Mark were "dissatisfied with their financial situation".
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL board of directors and, according to a biography published in 2015, Eddie McGirr, the TV star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin answered, texting, saying that since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really don't have much to say".
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and to tarnish our family name in court", he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his statement that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father would not want to see Paul and I argue in court", he said, adding that he "still hopes for a resolution of the conflict".
By Friday, that hope had apparently dissipated.
"The court will soon rule on our case", wrote Colin.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit information to the president.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly will actually do it.
In that case, he'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media, in hopes of keeping the chief more calm.
This is from reporter Josh Doosey.
"In a meeting that the new White House chief of staff John F. Kelly held with White House officials on his first day in office, he identified the main problem in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to solve: poor channels of information to the president".
Kelly told his staff that information should come through him - on paper or through briefings - because the president would be better at making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is perfectly correct, but others have already failed to appease Trump by tracking his information.
President Trump's relationship with television dates back decades - and now that he's in the White House, his TV habit is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, was outraged by unfair campaign coverage, it was helpful to show him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded", Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico that "six former campaign staffers said that to keep Trump's Twitter habits in check, we needed to ensure that the personal information he received was a constant stream of praise".
I'll be right there.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habits were ever "under control" is just ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign staffers know something we don't, like that, if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets that Trump didn't post.
If his associates have saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts have been worthwhile.
But no one could always stop Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by providing Trump with material - credible or not - that supports their views.
Politico, which was about this story, reported in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly feed the president questionable information.
Here's an example, reported by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Trump's current and former aides say Trump can react very harshly to negative media reports, especially dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who is behind them.
This happened in late February when someone handed the president a printed article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Kathy Welsh was accused of being "behind a series of leaks" at the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson was banned from Twitter forever for aggressive behavior, that he didn't present concrete facts, or that he made false accusations in the past and then denied them.
Trump read the article and started asking employees about Welsh".
Goldmacher adds that then-chief of staff Raines Priebus and secretary of the Treasury Rob Porter "tried to build a system to manage the flow of papers that Trump receives and document them".
How'd that work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
Tyumen prosecutor 's office is fighting HIV-dissident
The prosecutor's office challenged the decision of the Kalinin district court of Tyumen to dismiss the criminal case against a local woman whose young daughter died of HIV.
The investigation claims that the child died because the mother was an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court acquitted her of the charges because she had reconciled with her father.
The prosecution believes that the crime cannot go unpunished, lest it set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against the Tyumen resident was initiated under part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (cause of death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection in the 4B stage.
According to the prosecutor's office, the mother herself is HIV positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist", - explained in the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region.
The criminal case was submitted to the Kalininsky district court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that he "forgave his wife, has no complaints against her, she has compensated for the damage and apologized".
The prosecutor's office did not agree with the court's decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be reversed and sent for a new hearing.
The girl is dead, and the damage done by the crime is irreparable.
The mother, who is HIV-positive, has refused to examine her baby and treat her for a dangerous infection, despite the advice of doctors", the prosecutor's office said.
The watchdog says she should be punished or other HIV dissidents will follow.
According to the AIDS Center in Tyumen, about 12 HIV-positive children in the Tyumen region are currently not receiving medical care because of their parents' refusal.
"The situation has improved - within a year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who had refused to treat their children for HIV changed their minds - they were allowed to be diagnosed and started taking medication", said Elena Loseva, a spokeswoman for the AIDS Center.
She said it is impossible to legislate on parents, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children are detected - mothers are not allowed to examine them, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents ?
Late last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first study in Russia of the so-called HIV-dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and AIDS-serving NGOs call such views anti-medical and see their spread as a serious threat.
The horrific photo shoot, which ended in tragedy, took place on Thursday, August 3, at the Grečani railway station in Khmelnytsk.
