Italy is tightening its tone on NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue operating unless they comply with new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities", Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
The warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has been in operation for just over a year, declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"Saving lives is and will remain our top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our search and rescue activities now", the organization said in a statement on social media.
"We can only assess all the allegations now, "after we have gathered all the information and we can assess the situation".
Italian authorities have been tracking the Juventus vessel, owned by Jugend Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board in whole lifeboats, which were sent directly to them by human traffickers, and allowing the smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, which was published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the directives of the Italian coastguard, which oversees rescue operations in the area, out of humanitarian zeal rather than any other motive.
The code of conduct essentially stipulates that ships like the Juve will have an Italian police officer on board to supervise their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in the search and rescue have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, Malta's MOAS and Spain's Pro-Activa Extended Arms.
The latter said on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided they did not cause any "significant changes or interference" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy in recent weeks as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coastguard and cooperate with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In recent days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel", the minister said.
He announced plans to hold further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any side in the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations from opposing Libyan sides have visited Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, the assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told "Ъ", what goals Moscow pursues in this region and who it is betting on.
We know almost nothing about the Libya contact group you're leading.
Let's say the Ukraine contact group -- everybody knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was created at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya - "Ъ").
The latter is authorized to work on the Libyan direction by the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The group was formed after the detention of the Russian tanker "Mekanik Chebotaarev" in Libya (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Ъ").
We've been thinking about how we can help the crew.
Then a contact group of military experts, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you come to be the one in charge?
Since I've been working on Libya since 2008, I've been asked to lead the team.
Our activities were not limited to the release of the sailors from the "Mechanic Chebotarev".
We have managed to establish contacts with all the main groups opposed to each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognised government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based. - "Ъ") and Tobruk (the seat of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya - "Ъ").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya's deputy prime minister - "Ъ"), we managed to quickly agree on the release of the Russian sailors.
And so it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Her job is to analyze the situation, identify key players and factors, and engage with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any side in the conflict, we are in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are five people in the contact group now.
Among them are people with experience in law enforcement, including the Defense Ministry.
We also want to bring in a group of experts from the region, representatives of the Middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
There's no permanent staff in Libya, so there's no need for that.
Are there any Russian military advisors, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, whose side are you on?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and all the publicity about it is not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed to us for a while, like Misurata (where militia units are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and have been significantly activated in the years since).
We came to Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, told that it was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why these rumors are going around, what the role of the Islamists really is.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the teams that were involved in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned Islamic State - Kommersant).
We wanted to look at them, get to know these people, verify the information that they were the ones who played a crucial role in taking out ISIS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who claimed credit for it.
And what did you conclude?
Is it Haftar who won the Islamic State in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar was conducting operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by the government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we invited the people who were conducting this counterterrorism operation to Russia.
And they came - the visit lasted from April 19 to 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Rosgvardi.
We understand that you've been to all the regions of Libya and you probably know the mood of the local elites and field commanders.
Do you think that the ceasefire and elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarraj reached in Paris at the end of July will be implemented?
Or will agreements be broken, fighting resume, and the parties try to take power alone?
It's a good sign for us that Saraj and Haftar have agreed to meet again, which was not possible until recently.
In the recent past, both leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, and many believe this.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that very day.
It was a coincidence.
But the Misurans didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people to come to us today".
But our task is precisely to show that we are not only supporting Haftar, we are engaging with all key actors in the Libyan conflict.
You and Haftar were in touch.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make it easier for him to understand his Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
Russian, if he knows it, is very relative.
But what he's learned from us, of course, makes it easier to talk to him.
And not just him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who were either trained in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian perfectly.
And they're reaching for Russia, feeling a little nostalgic for it.
Do you think the arms embargo on Libya is likely to be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in Russian arms supplies?
They are, of course, but as I said, we are not taking sides in this conflict and we do not want to arm one to the detriment of the other.
We'd like to see everyone in a more or less equal position.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from Libyans for Russia to help lift it.
The process of drafting a constitution is now in full swing in Libya.
We hope the parties will reach a compromise, an internal consensus.
Then there should be elections, as was discussed at the meeting between Sarraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and now neither side has such a status), then the issue of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Security Council.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now, it will only escalate the conflict.
The media recently reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by its EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties to the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the possibility that Haftar's forces will take control of the coast and end the smuggling business that smuggles immigrants to Europe?
That's a very timely question.
We're actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is engaged in dialogue with Haftar, Sarajevo, Misrata and the south of the country.
And the tribes in southern Libya have a big role to play in this, and they're willing to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the southerners cutting off the flow of migrants at the far reaches?
So, technically, they turned back the buses carrying Nigerian migrants?
We're working on it.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help bring the southerners together in a negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes to the south.
But first, we'd like to see some consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
Tripoli's prime minister, Faiz Sarraj, is considered an Islamist and supporter of the introduction of sharia law.
How radical is he?
Would this not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself maintains that Libya should be a perfectly normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get that reputation?
It's created by countries that have no interest in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, the seat of the legislative, executive and judicial branches.
There's the national oil corporation, the national bank and other government agencies.
Of course, some countries had an interest in keeping us out.
And we've been playing cards with them and we've been actively communicating with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with the Libyan state oil company NOC.
NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft chief Igor Sechin was making a deal, is himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with her?
I guess I'll resell.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
The agreement is based on the previous agreements in the transport sector (building of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have money to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, like Iran, is this an oil-for-services scheme?
I don't know what the pattern is, but I'm not really into that stuff.
Actually, the economy is not the most important thing for Russia in Libya.
We're basically doing peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to reconcile among themselves so that they can establish order in their own country and Libya ceases to be a fertile environment for terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and drive the terrorists out.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, there are no people from Russia or other countries of the former USSR there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups in Libya and no Russian was spoken.
What country are these fighters from?
I'd rather not go into that detail.
Well, let's put it another way.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans?
There are hardly any Libyans among them, no more than 5%.
The rest are visitors.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan negotiations like Paris?
That's the plan.
We are in active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have expressed their readiness to come again - to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such a negotiation take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still a few visits to be made, and then I hope we can get some clarity on when and where the talks will take place.
