Michelle Carter sentenced for the messages that led to Conrad Roy's suicide.
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by texting and calling.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday: "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend".
Carter was allowed to remain at large pending appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, wearing red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, her arms folded and her eyes down.
"She killed Conrad Roy", the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She has not admitted responsibility", she said.
"She showed no remorse".
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic incident that she deeply regrets".
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said that in his opinion, her "age, maturity, or even mental illness did not significantly influence her actions".
The prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, which said: "Not a day has passed that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm doing - I'm trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever".
Roy's sister Camden Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or be his children's aunt.
"Losing the person who was always with me from the day I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life", she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, since Massachusetts has no law that would hold a person liable for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in his car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17.
The case drew national attention when it was revealed that Carter's suicide note had been the impetus.
"You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself, I don't know how many ways there are", she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was on vacation with his family.
Minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You must do this, Conrad", and "You only have to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy".
Judge Moniz said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy's death, and he banned her from talking to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers are divided on the matter.
One of the few to defend Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, wrote in the Los Angeles Times that "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison".
