Astronomers have found a planet that's a hell, and it's even capable of melting iron
When they first studied the stratosphere properties of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were surprised by its temperature, which is capable of evaporating iron and other metals.
The researchers noted that water molecules are heated by the starlight to such an extent that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Space Telescope captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: the high temperature that causes the water in the planet's atmosphere to glow in the infrared.
WASP-121b belongs to the so-called "hot Jupiters", gas giants that are comparable in size and mass to the largest planet in the Solar System but are located dozens of times closer to their parent star.
Because of this, the year on the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "Earth" days", and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change is threatening the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but now fears are being raised that it is threatened by climate change.
The drought and disease-carrying insects have made the lavender's growth worse, causing a constant headache for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Schess, an expert at the CRIEPPAM agricultural research institute in Provence, says: "The lavender in Provence is really under threat because in recent years the plant has been suffering from the effects of climate change, with much less rainfall in the spring and especially in the fall.
It affects the life of the lavender.
And there are little cycads that jump on leaves, carrying microorganisms, and they get very big in very dry weather".
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender is not only a tourist attraction; lavender oil is also a popular perfume and cosmetic product.
Says Eric Sess: "Instead of very long stems with many large flowers, we have small ones, underdeveloped, weakened or none at all.
So we have fewer parts that contain essential oil".
Solutions now being considered include improving water distribution and slowing soil evaporation, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more drought-resistant varieties.
