The violence is raging, and among the bodies that are growing in the country are more and more journalists: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and at least seven people have been killed in seven states this year.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, "RioDose" co-founder Javier Valdés Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist", Valdés wrote in one of his many books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very acutely, although his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdés, pointing his middle finger, with the words "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Riodos building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wearing T-shirts that show his smile, face in glasses or his signature Panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; the journalists discuss their shared trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was established in 2010 to investigate journalists, so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of murders committed each year in connection with drug trafficking and organized crime, journalists' killers are rarely brought to justice.
The journalists of Riodos insist on reporting on the violence in Sinaloa, even though they are killed by grief, even though it is much more dangerous now.
Without information about the killers, without justice, the security talks at the meetings are of little use", says Ibarra.
"It's stupid to waste time in this workshop", he says.
"Until we know the cause, we suspect everyone".
On the morning of May 15, Valdes left the Riodos office in Culiacan, the state capital.
He only managed to drive a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's title - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove off in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdés was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumors usually spread quickly around Culiacan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdes.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the US last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions battle to fill the vacuum.
Not to mention the fact that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with ornate two-story mausoleums of drug lords that are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let's forget for a minute that a state of calm is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdés was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is overwhelmed with guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel that is fighting the Guzman Sons.
The publication could have angered the sons; people who were supposedly gang members bought all the copies as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he didn't force Valdes to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that was covering the same story was seized.
Valdés was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He'd been out of danger so long, his friends and colleagues thought he'd be forever.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and in 2003 he and five colleagues founded Riodos, selling his $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without talking about drugs", said Bohorquez.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for being bold and honest, and sales and advertising revenue grew.
Journalists loved the fact that they could report bold stories without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that they could read about things that no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Riodosse received the prestigious Maria Murs Cabo Award for its reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdés won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating the drug trade in Mexico, wherever it led.
He frankly admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to move on", he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life", he said in an interview with Rompeviento TV last October.
"You must accept the tasks that are placed upon you as a journalist, either that or you are just being a fool".
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
The Riodos staff misses Valdés, a joker who was a hardened porter, a friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on the order they had established.
He had to wear his hat at all times.
He was supposed to go to El Guayabo, the bar across the street from his office, and always sit at the same table.
Now they ask, was he destroyed by his love of the once established order?
His death also made them question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
"They don't like you to know about their wives, their children, their legitimate businesses and their underground drug airfields.
"These things were over the line", said Bohorkes.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and a drive for self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from anything that smells bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andres Villarreal, is that "the smell can be deceived... and then what happened to Javier happens".
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states with a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak government institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
The room where Riodos staff were gathered for security training was suddenly forbidden to bring cell phones: days before, it was revealed that spyware, which is sold exclusively to governments, is being used in Mexico to spy on journalists and activists.
Outside , two policemen are hiding in the shade of a tree from the 104 degree heat .
They were assigned by the state government to guard the Riodos office, which is in a four-story building in the middle of the Kulikakan neighborhood.
Some reporters half-jokingly asked if these policemen were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officials the governor himself said could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue, "Ryodos" was expected to have three main themes.
It's the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio César Chávez.
They also had a government expenditure exposure centered in the governor's hometown.
And there was a gang kidnapping at one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the DA's office.
There was no official announcement of who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from public databases that the restaurant was registered to a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for most of the past century.
Several PRI governors have recently been the subject of high-profile corruption charges.
Villarreal asked reporters to cover previous incidents at the restaurant, including the time when Guzman's "El Chapo" son escaped a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have looked for Valdes' column with the most reliable information about a kidnapping.
"We would have known what happened before", says Villarreal, 46, nicknamed "El Flaco" for his slender build.
"All communication with our sources is cut today".
Valdes' office is now used as a storage facility for posters and stickers protesting the killing of journalists, because the staff have become what they never thought they would be: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took some posters and went to a demonstration at the local prosecutor's office the next morning to honor another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacán in the west of the country three days after Valdés was killed.
They found a burnt body, and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists have been speaking out, organizing protests and writing "SOS Press" on sidewalks and walls.
Director Bohorquez was in Washington that day, trying to rally international support to demand justice in the Valdes case.
In a meeting with Sinaloa's governor the day after Valdés's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their deaths for telling the truth.
She then asked not to be given any more government coverage, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdés has said many times that journalists in Mexico are "surrounded" by organized crime, its accomplices in government and indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just killed by drug gangs; they are killed by politicians and security services who are in league with organized crime.
The Article 19 Press Protection Committee estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
"In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up", Ramirez says.
Of course, murders scare people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, supposedly written by the Zetas cartel: "I'm here for my articles".
A computer keyboard and headphones were found next to her severed head.
Some newspapers chose to close down, like El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Brech was murdered in March.
Others continue to hold on, like El Manjana of Nuevo Laredo after its leader was murdered in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed the drug cartels with an editorial on the front page titled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It's a painful decision.
It's hard to find work in exile, and they still find danger on the streets.
And sometimes they get killed, as apparently happened with photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four other women in a Mexican apartment three months after he fled Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work are balancing risky decisions every day.
Ibarra, who once dreamed of being a poet, admits that he is afraid to write about the drug trade.
"Mexico is going to hell, and that's why I became a journalist", he says.
Last Friday at midnight, when the last issue was ready for print, the editors of the Riodos were sitting on the sidewalk near their office drinking beer when their phones rang at the same time.
A series of shootings between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Masatlan have left 19 dead, according to confirmed reports.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of cartel messages discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted news on the website Riodosse via mobile phone.
The next day, I had to rewrite the front page.
Sirens have gone off nearby, another shooting in the area.
Bochorkes checked to see if the police guarding them were ready to defend themselves.
If they were scared, they didn't show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to view throughout Sinaloa, the Riodos staff continued his work.
"How can you think of shutting down", said Bohorquez, "when the same day Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send her outside to do a story?"
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies.
At first glance, it appears to be a statue, though it is terrifying.
Researchers say the first remains of an incredible rhinos-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner were so well preserved that experts have dubbed it the "Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved that they could even identify that the color of its scaly skin was reddish-brown and say that it had, in a way, a dark past.
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best preserved of the Tireophores in all the history of finds and one of the best specimens of dinosaurs in the world".
This is a recently discovered fossil of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredible condition has stunned researchers who call it "really remarkable".
This herbivorous tireophor is the best preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the discovery, according to articles in National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Sancor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed different from the surrounding rock and decided to look more closely.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tirrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years , work was underway to find an animal weighing 2,500 feet (1100 kilograms) inside the earthenware.
Now that all that hard work is done, the finished product can be demonstrated.
"Just a little squint and you can almost believe it's asleep", said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creature is on display.
It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved specimens of dinosaurs.
By examining its skin, researchers found that this herbivore, although it was covered in a shell and resembled a walking tank, was apparently in significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful-armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a protective technique known as protective dye, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to blend in more quickly and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature from the Nodosaurus family was widely reported in the press in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of Mark Mitchell, a museum lab technician who spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly excavating it.
The remarkable preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on its body.
They found protective dye, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its bottom.
Although the protective dye is widespread, the discovery was a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than the size of any animal currently living with the protective dye.
It's possible that this dinosaur was so heavily hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution chose to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration - such as deer, zebras, or armored vehicles - are much smaller and more accessible prey, suggesting that the nodosaurus had to fight hard for survival.
"The serious threat from predators to the massive, powerful-shell dinosaur shows just how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous Period were", Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for clues to its life, including what remains of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They think that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was washed out to sea, where it sank and lay on its back on the ocean floor.
In those days, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida is now, and rivers and oceans likely extended farther inland than they do now.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original animal form", Brown said.
The result is that the animal now looks almost exactly as it did back then, in the Early Cretaceous.
It doesn't take much imagination to recreate it, just a little nudging, and you can almost believe it's asleep.
The Cretaceous is the time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that stood on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the thyreophorus may have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
Among them is the acrocanthosaurus, a monster that measures 38 feet (11.5 meters) long and weighs six tons.
Scientists whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology believe that Borealopelta was carried to the sea after death and mummified in mud.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved thyreophore in the world, along with the skin and armor, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the femur.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spines protruding from their shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore trampled heavily on what is now Canada until a flooded river washed it out to sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its shell to the last detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bulging shell plates along the dinosaur's skull.
As Michael Gresko wrote in an article for National Geographic, such a degree of preservation is "as rare as winning the lottery".
The longer I look at it, the more amazing it seems.
The fossilized remains of the skin still cover the bulging shell plates that dot the animal's skull.
His right front leg is extended along the side, five fingers on it facing up.
I can count the scales on his sole.
