How did one activist find the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to her core.
Just one day after arriving in New York City on a tourist trip, the St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an Airbnb apartment, looking at Facebook on her phone.
She ran into a post from high school.
It said, "Police just killed an 18-year-old kid, and he's still lying in the middle of the street".
Noticing that no one else from her feed had posted this information, she was puzzled and closed her Facebook and opened Twitter.
Her video featured a lot of user posts with the nickname @TheePharoah.
A rapper from the Greater St. Louis area tweeted live about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black teenager killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's lifeless body lying in the street for four hours.
"This is wild", Ferrell thought.
But death was not new to her and her circle.
She hung up and later that night, she went back to tweeting about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of the signal tape and people screaming and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a sign that said, "Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, pulled the trigger and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals!"
"This is an unusual situation", Ferrell recalled.
This is not a murder like the ones we're used to, which we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt a chill.
I was angry and I cried.
She took a return flight and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, due out on August 11.
It's a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience from the perspective of people living in the community and filling the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a colorful wreath, they recalled a conversation they had had that morning, countless times, about the experience of black people and their condition.
She remembers saying, "Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson now because a cop killed an 18-year-old boy, and it was wrong.
"I couldn't help but take it", Ferrell said later.
What's happening today is the culmination of what's happened before.
She needs to know it, see it, and grow up with it.
She needs to be not only well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their situation and what we need to do to become free, to be free.
Even if I can provide her with an environment where she herself will not face overt racism, she is no different than any other black girl.
I feel like I'd be doing her a disservice if I kept her out of it.
When they arrived in Ferguson, their first stop was on South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station that had become something of a tent camp while activists waited for word of the ultimate acquittal of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local businessman who was preparing lunch packages.
They collected the bags and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, a new kind of activism took shape in Ferrell's mind.
"My activism changed completely after August 9", she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the National Minority Health Students Association and worked for food equity and health inequality in black communities.
I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Saba'a Folayyan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her chief cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Ferrare "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell had this question in his head: "Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?"
This skepticism was fueled by the many people, often white, who came to the community to take advantage of his pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson were not being heard, and we wanted to do something different".
By that time, Foley had teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His participation sparked sympathy for the project among Ferrell and six other local residents, with whom the Whose Streets? project team maintained contact for years after Brown's murder.
"In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, we speak for ourselves", Davis said.
It was the most important thing for me to be represented by these people, because that's how I'm going to be represented.
And while the project was not intended to focus on Ferrell's experience at all, in an effort to show that the movement is not about a leader-savior, but about how a community comes together, Folayan said she was the most open-minded of the film's participants.
The resulting Whose Streets? shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love and married her husband.
"I felt naked", said Ferrell, laughing as she recalled seeing the finished product for the first time.
But I knew that when you do this kind of work and you humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.
Furthermore, Ferrell's story again discusses and emphasizes the role of the black homosexual woman in the broader context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created the #BlackLivesMatter social media hashtag after the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin - identify as gay.
"Black, lesbian women in leadership positions are supporting this whole movement", says Ferrell. "It's because we're fighting on multiple fronts all the time.
Black gay women have to carry all this burden.
Folayan agreed with this statement, noting that the movement is actually supported by black women and many homosexual black women.
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination" and that Ferrell was not chosen as the central character of the film because of her distinctive features.
"She was the person who awakened that energy", she said.
On the other hand, it's no coincidence that she's in the foreground, because when
You can feel the energy through the screen.
Meanwhile, Ferguson has long since been without movie cameras, but there remain complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrell's on probation for another two and a half years for blocking the highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place she calls home, simply: Bardak.
She's still holding on to the language she learned when she walked down the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We should love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.
