The emergence of a similarity: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning 's DNA
In the center of the room at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hanging from the ceiling on the wire -- white, black and brown, all looking somewhat similar.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clippings from Fort Leavenworth, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the infamous WikiLeaks leak of classified diplomatic cables.
The new exhibition, which opens August 2, is called "The Emergence of Similarity".
It's the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and prominent dissident whose sentence was commuted by Barack Obama just three days before his presidency ended.
By analyzing the DNA program Manning had provided and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of people who might have had this genome, Dewey-Harborg created a profound, though hard-to-understand, manifesto about not only the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways it is interpreted and the inherent determinism of those interpretations - but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but openly identified as a woman since her teens, was convicted in 2013 of 20 counts, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie of Manning in a platinum wig, clearly feeling awkward behind the wheel of a car, which became associated with her.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project "Visions of Strangers".
In it, she created portraits of unknown people using evidence from court cases, such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from the rubbish and creating images of what those people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some kind of portrait to illustrate the article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new exhibition for the press.
Chelsea was not allowed to visit and take pictures at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to have a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book called Repressed Images, illustrated by Sholi Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president would ease Chelsea's sentence and she would be able to visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama actually decided to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven years of hard labor in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something profound and powerful about this exhibition opening at a time when Donald Trump is declaring war on people who leak government secrets and inventing new ways to fuel the enmity he's supposed to be softening on Twitter.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that "nothing happens by chance".
In a statement by the artist, written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of the dot above the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic segregation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture".
On the other side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long cluster of C, G and A pencil prints.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist so scientifically expresses it), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how amazingly similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not define who we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Harborg, whose 2007 video work, False Memories, is also on display here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here".
The last part of the exhibition, which was in one room, is the comic book novel mentioned above.
It shows Manning in a King Kong style, standing over the U.S. Correctional Building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they win", it says.
"So never shut up".
"It's a direct quote from a letter she wrote me", says the artist who greets us from Philadelphia.
"I still get the chills when I talk about it".
Manning has yet to see the exhibition in person - as the comics so presciently portrayed - but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacrums, gathered like a crowd of protesters.
This was done on purpose, as was everything in the exhibit, right down to the height of the pencil that had the genetic haplogroups drawn on.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd", says Dewey-Harborg of the portraits.
