To create a comic novel: One castle in English history
In the recent past, the tiny Scottney Castle was featured in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s, it was a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy home in the Beul River valley in Kent, he has watched the tumultuous history around him, and now he has inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a thick head of hair and a penchant for historical documents, to write a comic novel.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago", he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personal when you hold this letter in your hand".
The castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells the story of the families who lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This isn't Rhodes' first book to draw on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories", a collection of British Library documents that touched him unexpectedly.
"I could scratch a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700's by a double agent working for the Jacobites", he says.
"It's his fingerprint".
And the letters always smell like smoke because they used to light fires in those days.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you feel like you're there too.
Oh, how I love the archives!"
For someone so obsessed with old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the Arts Council England and living in a castle for four months ("I actually stayed there for a bit") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days exploring the "new" Victorian castle, going through archives and examining the estate's many treasures and antiquities - such as the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had been lying in a ditch for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drink whiskey and sit down to write".
Scotney Castle's history is not well studied, because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only just begun to dig into what he described as "something that aristocrats have been putting in the attic for centuries".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring", says Rhodes, "but there were two families fighting over this birch.
It happens, guys!"
In some of the stories in the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations in English history: for example, in The Workman, the hero leaves a newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolution of 1381.
"There is a record of a rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising had begun in these places, and I thought that the uprising was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the castle's history - for example, "The Priest", which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden away by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with rocks (this was discovered years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells were Rhodes' favorite family of all the Scotties: "The gentlemen seemed to be the ultimate cheaters, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, the Darrel men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women - I imagine them as a company of handsome guys who know how to take care of heirs of great fortunes".
After leaving the castle, Rhodes searches for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish countryside, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmaki, a place where a sanatorium once stood at the beginning of the 20th century, but which was then again overgrown with forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave", he says.
"I was like, 'Damn, I need to get back to real life.'"
