Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help alleviate IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help to alleviate symptoms in those with inflammatory bowel disease.
This chronic condition, which affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although people are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy to relieve symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid, tryptophan, promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, the lead researcher, explained that immune cells in the gut keep harmful foodborne microbes from entering the body.
The cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body while not harming sensitive tissue.
If the balance is too much off in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a particular bacteria in their gut develop resistance-enhancing cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to trigger the formation of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice ate, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the same thing would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Later, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of immune cell types that increase resistance, found that one group of mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same lineage but was kept separate, did not.
She suggested that the difference may be caused by the gut microbiome of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of mice was sequenced, and they found six types of bacteria that are present in mice that have immune cells, but not in mice that don't have them.
Mice raised in sterile environments that didn't have a good microbiome and didn't develop this type of immune cell got L. reuteri, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small amounts of the fluid - free of bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells have turned into tolerance-boosting cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same resistance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri promote cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people with inflammatory bowel disease, defects in tryptophan-associated genes have been found.
She says: "Perhaps we need to increase the development of these cells, since they are the key to inflammation on the inner surface of the intestine.
High tryptophan levels in L. reuteri could potentially lead to an increase in their population".
