The props for the White House cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars .
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American manufacturing cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials have inspected technology products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed alongside a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi truck.
According to records from the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for controlling the helicopter, the White House War Office ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual, widely covered event", the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his commanding officer, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in the event, which was scheduled for 3 p.m., and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the hours of operation restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was unclear from the records obtained by TIME magazine whether a second crew was needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the event violates this order.
"We asked if it was a violation of the Hatch Act, among other things, and we were told no", the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have a place to hide", replied the deputy.
The Made in America event was declared an official event by the White House, and it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance health care reform, which was then in the works in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them solely for the sake of photography.
Trump was already the subject of controversy in February when a presidential plane flew in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about his predecessor using the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled with the Made in America showcase, which features products from all 50 states made by American workers from American materials", said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around Washington DC and the South Lawn to practice transporting the President of the United States to the White House with an inch of precision.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight performed for the "Made in America" event was counted as a month's worth of training flights.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of non-presidential support missions.
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits on display.
A representative of Sikorsky said the company had not participated in the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's rate of reimbursement for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
Unit records show the aircraft's time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base at Marine Corps Air Station Quantico, Virginia.
The White House claims the actual cost of using the helicopter is far below that rate.
"It is a complete mistake to calculate the cost to taxpayers based on a roughly approximate refund rate", says Walters.
These approximate rates include staff, maintenance and many other non-refundable costs that are included in the annual allocations.
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, the compensation rates do not include personnel costs, but do take into account fuel costs, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was speaking out in defense of using a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase this week's Made in America stuff", Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in the fact that they're contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans worked tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it's perfectly appropriate to pay attention to that.
It was unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in the driver's seat of the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed the Sikorsky representatives, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
"I know the Sikorsky", said the president. "I have three of them".
